"González-García S., Teresa Moreira M., Artal G., Maldonado L., Feijoo G.","Environmental impact assessment of non-wood based pulp production by soda-anthraquinone pulping process",2010,"Journal of Cleaner Production","18","2",,"137","145",,,10.1016/j.jclepro.2009.10.008,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70749106994&partnerID=40&md5=a1d8d5cd6251bfd9ab294aa694eca9e9","Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela., 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Celulosas de Levante SA (CELESA), Ctra. C-237, km 4.5, E-43500 Tortosa, Spain","González-García, S., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela., 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Teresa Moreira, M., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela., 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Artal, G., Celulosas de Levante SA (CELESA), Ctra. C-237, km 4.5, E-43500 Tortosa, Spain; Maldonado, L., Celulosas de Levante SA (CELESA), Ctra. C-237, km 4.5, E-43500 Tortosa, Spain; Feijoo, G., Department of Chemical Engineering, School of Engineering, University of Santiago de Compostela., 15782 Santiago de Compostela, Spain","Paper pulp manufacturing is the main non-food industrial utilization of plant biomass. Non-wood and agricultural residues are potential raw materials in the production of specialty papers. This chapter aims to quantify the environmental impacts associated with non-wood high quality paper pulp manufacture via soda-anthraquinone (AQ) cooking process by means of the application of LCA methodology in a cradle-to-gate analysis. Hemp (Cannabis sativa) and Flax (Linum usitatissimum) were evaluated as raw materials for the production of high quality non-porous pulp. A specialty paper pulp mill was analysed in detail and process chain was divided in six subsystems: agricultural activities, chemicals production, electricity production, transport, pulp production and waste treatment. Inventory data came from interviews and surveys (on-site measurements). When necessary, the data were completed with bibliographic resources. Abiotic resources depletion (AD), global warming (GW), ozone layer depletion (OLD), human toxicity (HT), ecotoxicity, photochemical oxidant formation (POF), acidification (A) and eutrophication (E) were the impact categories analysed in this study. According to the results, the environmental impact is mainly caused by the production of chemicals, electricity and fibres (agricultural activities) due to greenhouse gases emissions, phosphorous and nitrogen compounds emissions. The activities inside the pulp mill present minor contribution to almost all impact categories, excluding GW (15%) and E (6%) as well as OLD (25%). This study provides useful information for non-wood based industries related not only to pulp manufacture but also to panels or biorefineries with the aim of increasing their sustainability. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","AQ; Cooking process; Environmental impact; Flax; Hemp; Soda-anthraquinone; Specialty paper pulp","Agricultural activities; Agricultural residue; AQ; Biorefineries; Cannabis sativa; Cooking process; Ecotoxicity; Electricity production; Greenhouse gases emissions; High quality; High quality papers; Human toxicity; Industrial utilization; Inventory data; Linum usitatissimum; Non-wood; On-site measurement; Ozone layer depletion; Paper pulp; Photochemical oxidants; Plant biomass; Process chain; Pulp mill; Pulp production; Pulping process; Resources depletion; Agricultural wastes; Biomass; Environmental impact; Environmental impact assessments; Eutrophication; Flax; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Hemp; Industrial waste treatment; Ketones; Linen; Nitrogen compounds; Ozone; Ozone layer; Paper; Paper and pulp mills; Phosphorus; Pulp materials; Toxicity; Wood; Yarn; Pulp cooking; Agriculture; Biomass; Eutrophication; Flax; Greenhouse Gases; Hemp; Ketones; Lin